# Command dsw

## What does this command do:

A webhook for command line commands defined by YAML

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: curl -sSfL https://github.com/overthinkinglabs/dsw/releases/download/v0.0.3/dsw_0.0.3_linux_amd64.tar.gz -o /tmp/dsw.tar.gz && tar -xzf /tmp/dsw.tar.gz -C ~/.local/bin/ && chmod +x ~/.local/bin/dsw
For Raspberry Pi install using: curl -sSfL https://github.com/overthinkinglabs/dsw/releases/download/v0.0.3/dsw_0.0.3_linux_arm64.tar.gz -o /tmp/dsw.tar.gz && tar -xzf /tmp/dsw.tar.gz -C ~/.local/bin/ && chmod +x ~/.local/bin/dsw
For Mac install using: curl -sSfL https://github.com/overthinkinglabs/dsw/releases/download/v0.0.3/dsw_0.0.3_darwin_arm64.tar.gz -o /tmp/dsw.tar.gz && tar -xzf /tmp/dsw.tar.gz -C ~/.local/bin/ && chmod +x ~/.local/bin/dsw

## Command path

For Fedora run: ~/.local/bin/dsw
For Raspberry Pi run: ~/.local/bin/dsw
For Mac run: ~/.local/bin/dsw

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://github.com/overthinkinglabs/dsw

## Command options

dsw create <name> <command>     # create a single action
dsw create -f <file.yaml>       # create actions from YAML file
dsw ls                          # list all available actions
dsw run <name>                  # execute an action locally
dsw serve [-p 8080] [-d]        # start HTTP API server (default port 4242; -d for daemon mode)
dsw stop                        # stop daemon server
dsw status                      # show daemon status
dsw boot enable [-p 8080]       # enable boot service
dsw boot disable                # disable boot service
dsw version                     # show version

# Trigger an action via HTTP once serve is running:
curl -X POST http://localhost:4242/execute/<action>
